<div itemprop="articleBody">
<h1>Tutorial 37. Manual Calculation of Pattern Adjustments.</h1>
<p><strong>In this tutorial, I want to remind you how to manually calculate pattern adjustments with a simple example. </strong>I will show you how we calculate adjustments to the standard patterns enclosed with this book or with any other book by the Corset Academy with regard to your client’s measurements.</p>
<p>Although this book includes an Automatic Pattern Adjustments Calculator, I still want to remind you (or maybe explain it for the first time for some of you) how you do these calculations manually.</p>
<p><strong>After finishing the calculations, we will compare their results with the results shown by the Automatic Calculator. </strong>We will also see in what cases the software fulfills all necessary tasks and in what cases you should step in and make certain adjustments yourself to ensure a flawless fit. On the other hand, we will also talk about possible defects by analyzing the values proposed by the software.</p>
<p><strong>Let us begin. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I have drawn a classic table with pattern measurements and client’s measurements on the writing board. </strong>I have taken a basic pattern with two bust princess seams, a low V-neck front, and a plain back made of four pieces.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>First of all, let us find the position of the front princess seam against the fold line of the centre front piece. </strong>I need to calculate the distance from the fold line to the princess seam in order to understand whether the initial pattern requires adjustments here.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Bust Princess Seam Width shows us where the bust princess seams are supposed to go.</strong></p>
<p>It is 18cm on my client and 19cm on the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>18cm – 19cm = -1cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>This means I need to remove 0.5cm from either side of the centre front piece. </strong></p>
<p>When I put the paper pattern to the fabric fold line, I will simply shift it 0.5cm so as to narrow the piece.</p>
<p><strong>I write -0.5cm in line 7 of column 3. </strong></p>
<p>But if I put the pattern to the fabric fold line this way, that 0.5cm will be removed along its full length. To keep this in mind, I put -0.5cm in all lines of the Bust Princess Seam Width column related to circumferences and affected by this adjustment.</p>
<p><strong>I have removed -0.5cm along the fold line of the centre front piece. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Now we need to find the position of the side seam.</strong> As you understand, the side seam is responsible for overall garment balance, appearance, overall fit, and bust fit. It is safe to say that its position is the key to all these things. Whether your garment will look professional or amateurish depends on how well you position the side seam. Therefore, we need to determine necessary adjustments to the standard pattern to position the side seam correctly on the client.</p>
<p><strong>Side seam position is determined by two measurements: Bust Width Front and Under-Bust Width Front. </strong>You need to find the difference between client’s measurements and pattern measurements. And, of course, you must remember that we have already removed 0.5cm from either side of the centre front piece thereby changing the distance between the princess seams.</p>
<p><strong>Bust Width Front.</strong></p>
<p>This measurement is 47cm on the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>How do you take it? </strong></p>
<p><strong>Imagine that you have sewn together the centre front piece and the side front piece. </strong>I mark section (a) along the bust line of the centre front piece (seam allowances excluded) and section (b) along the bust line of the side front piece (seam allowances also excluded).</p>
<p>The total length of (a) and (b) makes a half of the measurement and should thus be multiplied by 2.</p>
<p><strong>As the result, Bust Width Front of the pattern is as follows:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a + b) × 2 = 47cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>But the pattern has already been narrowed by 1cm at the bust line level (0.5cm from either side). </strong></p>
<p><strong>47cm – 1cm = 46cm</strong></p>
<p>My client’s Bust Width Front is 45cm.</p>
<p>Therefore:</p>
<p><strong>45cm – 46cm = -1cm</strong></p>
<p>I divide it in half between the two sides of the front. As the result, either side seam line of the front needs to be shifted 0.5cm inwards at the bust line level to put the side seam in place on my client’s body. I write -0.5cm in line 1 of column 4.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Under-Bust Width Front.</strong></p>
<p>My client’s measurement is 37cm and it is 38cm on the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>Under-Bust Width Front of the pattern is measured the same way as Bust Width Front only along the under-bust line. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Under-Bust Width Front of the pattern is as follows: </strong></p>
<p><strong>(a1 + b1) × 2 = 38cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>But the pattern has already been narrowed by 1cm at the under-bust line level (0.5cm from either side). </strong></p>
<p><strong>38cm – 1cm = 37cm</strong></p>
<p>Now the pattern measurement already coincides with my client’s measurement. <strong>This means I don’t need to make any other adjustments to put the side seam in place at the under-bust line level. </strong></p>
<p>I write a zero in line 2 of column 4.</p>
<p><strong>So I have determined </strong>that I need to remove half a centimeter from either side of the bust line and leave everything as is along the under-bust line to put the side seam where it should be on the client.</p>
<p><strong>I recommend you avoid changing the shape of the side seam apart from rare exceptional cases. </strong>It is easier to work with this pattern with this side seam shape.</p>
<p><strong>As the result, I need to decide </strong>whether I will remove that 0.5cm along the full front side seam line or leave everything as is because there are no adjustments at the under-bust level.</p>
<p><strong>I prefer to leave it as is. I write a zero in all relevant lines of column 4. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p>You can separate the top part of the table with Bust Width Front and Under-Bust Width Front because these measurements will not participate in further calculations. We will only work with the bottom part of the table from this moment on.</p>
<p><strong>So the front side seam line stays where it was on the standard pattern. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Let us move to the back.</strong></p>
<p><strong>I need to understand</strong> whether the position of the back side seam line must be adjusted or whether it can be left unchanged like the front side seam line. The remaining measurements and the adjustments already made to the front will answer this question.</p>
<p><strong>In simple terms, I need to understand where the back side seam line should be positioned at the level of each circumference line: bust line, under-bust line, waistline, and stomach line.</strong> After doing all calculations, I will find the side seam points along all these circumference lines with regard to client’s measurements.</p>
<p><strong>Let us start from the bust line, i.e. Bust Circumference. </strong></p>
<p>This measurement is 91cm on the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>It is taken the same way as Bust Width Front.</strong> I sum up the lengths of sections C and D on the centre back piece and the side back piece, add up the total length of sections A and B on the front pieces, and multiply it all by two.</p>
<p><strong>As the result, the pattern has the following Bust Circumference:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a + b + c + d) × 2 = 91cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>Under-Bust Circumference, Waist Circumference, and Stomach Circumference (taken 12cm below waistline) are measured just the same way on the pattern.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Let us start calculating. </strong>My client’s Bust Circumference is 83cm and it is 91cm on the pattern.</p>
<p>The centre front piece has already been narrowed by a total of 1cm (0.5cm from either side). There are no adjustments to the side seam line.</p>
<p><strong>91cm - 1cm = 90cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>83cm – 90cm = -7cm.</strong></p>
<p>As you can see, the pattern is still 7cm larger than needed at the bust line level despite the fact that I removed 0.5cm along the side of the front.</p>
<p>I divide this excess of 7cm in half between the two sides of the back (left and right). As the result, <strong>I need to shift the back side seam line 3.5cm inwards at the bust line level.</strong> I write -3.5cm in the Back Side Seam Line column.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Let us move to the under-bust line, i.e. Under-Bust Circumference. </strong>My client’s measurement is 71cm and it is 75cm on the pattern.</p>
<p>The centre front piece has already been narrowed by a total of 1cm (0.5cm from either side). There are no adjustments to the front side seam line.</p>
<p><strong>75cm - 1cm = 74cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>74cm – 71cm = -3cm.</strong></p>
<p>As you can see, the pattern is still 3cm larger than needed at the under-bust line level despite the fact that I removed 0.5cm along the side of the front.</p>
<p>I divide this excess of 3cm in half between the two sides of the back (left and right). As the result, <strong>I need to shift the back side seam line 1.5cm inwards at the under-bust line level.</strong> I write -1.5cm in the table.</p>
<p><strong>Next, let us look at the waistline or Waist Circumference. </strong>My client’s measurement is 67cm and it is 70cm on the pattern.</p>
<p>The centre front piece has already been narrowed by a total of 1cm (0.5cm from either side). There are no adjustments to the front side seam line.</p>
<p><strong>70cm - 1cm = 69cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>67cm – 69cm = -2cm.</strong></p>
<p>The pattern is still 2cm larger than needed in the waist even though I removed 0.5cm along the side of the front.</p>
<p>I divide this excess of 2cm between the two sides of the back (left and right). As the result, <strong>I need to shift the back side seam line 1cm inwards at the waistline level.</strong> I write -1cm in the table.</p>
<p><strong>The last circumference line is the stomach line. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Stomach Circumference is taken 12cm below waistline. </strong>It is 85cm on the client and 92cm on the pattern.</p>
<p>The centre front piece has already been narrowed by a total of 1cm (0.5cm from either side). There are no adjustments to the front side seam line.</p>
<p><strong>92cm - 1cm = 91cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>85cm – 91cm = -6cm.</strong></p>
<p>The pattern is still 6cm larger than needed in the stomach even though I removed 0.5cm along the side of the front.</p>
<p>I divide this excess of 6cm in half between the two sides of the back (left and right). As the result, <strong>I need to shift the back side seam line 3cm inwards at the stomach level.</strong> I write -3cm in the table.</p>
<p><strong>Let us analyze the results of our calculations.</strong> I had warned you against changing the initial shape of the side seam. But the calculated values show that the back side seam line of the adjusted pattern will be curvy and resemble a wave.</p>
<p><strong>I need to choose a fixed value by which I will shift the entire back side seam line based on all calculated adjustment values. </strong>Any of these values will do. As a rule, you should think over the style of your garment. For example, the side back piece will become very narrow if I shift the side seam line 3.5cm inwards. It is better to use a smaller value and then take in the princess seams.</p>
<p><strong>I believe 2cm is a suitable value in our simple case. I write -2cm in the Side Seam Adjusted Column. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>This means the entire back side seam line of the standard pattern will be shifted 2cm inwards. </strong>You can draw the new side seam line using the standard pattern as a template.</p>
<p>There are certain difficulties associated with calculations in this particular pattern. The back is low, the bust line is trimmed away, and it is hard to determine its precise position. But I have already told you that all my patterns are made of interchangeable pieces.</p>
<p>You can take the side piece from some other corset pattern (for example, the corset with shoulder or halter straps), put it over the basic piece, and draw the lacking parts of the back.</p>
<p>It will be easy to find and mark the bust line and the under-bust line after you do this.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Let us continue our calculations.</strong></p>
<p><strong>I return to the bust line.</strong></p>
<p>I have removed 2cm from either side of the back at the bust line level, but there is still an excess of 1.5cm left because I need to remove 3.5cm at that level.</p>
<p><strong>In this case, I can use the back princess seam. </strong>And if it happens to be not enough, then I can make additional adjustments to the front princess seams at the waistline and below.</p>
<p><strong>So there is an excess of 1.5cm at the bust line level on either half of the back.</strong> Either half of the back has one princess seam which joins together two edges.</p>
<p><strong>This means I need to remove about 0.7cm from either princess seam edge at the bust line level. I write -0.7cm in the Side Seam Back column. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Let us move to the under-bust line.</strong></p>
<p>I have removed 2cm from either side of the back at the under-bust line level. But the calculations show that I only need to remove 1.5cm there. The lacking 0.5cm needs to be restored.</p>
<p><strong>This means I need to shift either princess seam edge about 0.2cm outwards at the under-bust line level. I write 0.2cm in the Princess Seam Back column. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I move to the waistline.</strong></p>
<p>I have removed 2cm from either side of the back at the waistline level. But the calculations show that I only need to remove 1cm there. The lacking 1cm needs to be restored.</p>
<p><strong>This means I need to shift either princess seam edge 0.5cm outwards at the waistline level. I write 0.5cm in the Princess Seam Back column. </strong></p>
<p><strong>The last line is the stomach line.</strong></p>
<p>I have removed 2cm from either side of the back at the stomach level. According to the calculations, it should be 3cm. There is an excess of 1cm on the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>This means I need to shift either princess seam edge 0.5cm inwards at the stomach level. I write -0.5cm in the Princess Seam Back column.</strong></p>
<p><strong>And now I need to transfer all our calculations on the pattern, i.e. adjust the standard pattern accordingly. </strong></p>
<p><strong>The first thing I do is remove 0.5cm along the fold line of the centre front piece. The side seam line remains unchanged. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I shift the side seam line 2cm inwards on the side back piece. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Before shifting the princess seam lines, let us calculate Clip-related adjustments, i.e. determine cup length and volume.</strong></p>
<p><strong>I mark clips from the bust point on the front piece: </strong></p>
<p>- Clip toward Armscye - 10.5cm;</p>
<p>- Clip toward Top of Cup – 11.7cm, and</p>
<p>- Clip toward Middle of Neckline – 8cm.</p>
<p><strong>I calculate the difference between my client’s clip measurements and the pattern measurements and write the resulting values in the table. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Clip toward Armscye: </strong>9cm on the client and 10.5cm on the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>9cm – 10.5cm = -1.5cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>Clip toward Top of Cup: </strong>10cm on the client and 11.7cm on the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>10cm – 11.7cm = -1.7cm</strong></p>
<p><strong>Clip toward Middle of Neckline: </strong>7cm on the client and 8cm on the pattern.</p>
<p><strong>7cm – 8cm = -1cm</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image026.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I make corresponding adjustments to the standard pattern. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image028.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>And I re-draw the front pieces with regard to these adjustments.</strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image030.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>All I need to do is apply adjustments to the back princess seams.</strong></p>
<p>I have analyzed all calculated values and realized that the back princess seam line will be distorted if I shift it 0.5cm outwards at the waistline and 0.5cm inwards at the stomach line.</p>
<p>For this reason, I have decided to use the front princess seam lines and re-distribute the waist and stomach adjustment values. I will leave it at 0.3cm to either side for the back princess seam lines and shift the front princess seam line 0.3cm outwards at the waistline and 0.3cm inwards at the stomach line.</p>
<p><strong>I add a new column to the table, Princess Seam Front, and write down the new values. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image032.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I mark all adjustments to the front and back princess seam lines on the pattern and re-draw it accordingly. It is now fully customized to fit my client’s size. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2037.files/image034.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>

</div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody -->
